We pdeveloped a Comprehensive Corona and Heliosphere Model (CCHM). CCHM is driven by solar observations that are incorporated into a validated set of self-consistently coupled models. It is a comprehensive numerical model of the 3D time-dependent structure and dynamics of the corona and the solar wind. The main features of the model are:

A      3D quantitative description of the large scale structure and properties of      the corona and the heliosphere at any given instant in time;
It uses      presently available and forthcoming line-of-sight photospheric magnetic      field data, as well as vector magnetic field observations as input;
Initiate      simple transients, as well as sophisticated magnetically driven solar      eruptions;
Provide      predictions of time dependent solar wind parameters at a point or an      object (Earth, Mars, spacecraft) in space including the energetic particle      environment;
Be      sufficiently modular to incorporate routines containing new or more      sophisticated physics;
A      user-friendly web portal to create, submit, monitor and analyze runs      (including graphics) by the general research community;
Runs      faster than real-time on reasonable computational resources, thus it has the flexibility for quick-turn-around runs;
Runs      continuously in a "pipeline mode." The model allows us to describe the      continuous topological changes of the solar magnetic field;
We delivered a working version to the CCMC and it is applying rigorous evaluation and      validation procedures.


